The paper proposes a novel approach to implementing logical gates using plant roots, which falls under the category of morphological computing. This interdisciplinary field combines biology and computer science, making cs.ET (Emerging Technologies) a likely sub-category. The use of plant roots also involves aspects of neural networks and robotics, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.RO (Robotics) possible sub-categories. The proposed gates involve interaction between roots, which can be seen as a system of control, making cs.SY (Systems and Control) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the study of plant biology and its application to computing, making cs.BIO (Bioinformatics) a possible sub-category as well.
